%S A319476 0,1,2,2,3,5,5,6,5,7,9,7,8,11,13,9,11,14,16,17,19,21,21,14,14,16,19,
%T A319476 16,18,21
%N A319476 a(n) is the minimum number of distinct distances between n non-attacking rooks on an n X n chessboard.
%C A319476 a(n) <= n - 1, which is the number of distinct distances the rooks are placed along a diagonal.
%C A319476 Conjecture: a(n^2) = A047800(n-1) - 1. - _Peter Kagey_, Nov 02 2018
%C A319476 From _Martin Fuller_, May 02 2026: (Start)
%C A319476 Some results and questions about grid-based arrangements:
%C A319476 A square grid separated by (a,b) can fill the board iff |a^2+b^2-n| <= 1 and a,b are coprime (cf A008784). This is optimal for n=9..14 and others. Consider an n x n window into the infinite version of this grid:
%C A319476 * If n=a^2+b^2+1 then the window must contain a rook at each corner, and two opposite corners must be omitted on the board.
%C A319476 * If n=a^2+b^2 then any window can be used. Some may have fewer distances than others.
%C A319476 * If n=a^2+b^2-1 then the window must be placed with a rook just outside each corner.
%C A319476 A rectangular grid separated by (a,1) and (-1,a)*c can be used iff |(a^2+1)c-n| <= 1 and a,c are coprime. This is optimal for n=19..21. If n=(a^2+1)c+1 then two opposite corners must be omitted.
%C A319476 A rhomboid grid with diagonal symmetry can do better than n-1. Examples: n=7,8,15,23. What are the requirements for this pattern?
%C A319476 Are there any other patterns that can do better than n-1? (End)
%H A319476 Martin Fuller, <a href="/A319476/a319476.cpp.txt">C++ program</a>
%H A319476 Martin Fuller, <a href="/A319476/a319476.svg">Illustration of A319476 n=1..30</a>
%H A319476 Giovanni Resta, <a href="/A319476/a319476.pdf">Illustration of a(3)-a(14)</a>
%e A319476 For n = 7 a board with a(7) = 5 distinct distances is
%e A319476   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A319476 7 |   |   | * |   |   |   |   |
%e A319476   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A319476 6 |   |   |   |   |   | * |   |
%e A319476   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A319476 5 | * |   |   |   |   |   |   |
%e A319476   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A319476 4 |   |   |   | * |   |   |   |
%e A319476   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+.
%e A319476 3 |   |   |   |   |   |   | * |
%e A319476   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A319476 2 |   | * |   |   |   |   |   |
%e A319476   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A319476 1 |   |   |   |   | * |   |   |
%e A319476   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A319476     A   B   C   D   E   F   G
%e A319476 The distances between pairs of points are:
%e A319476 1)   sqrt(10) (e.g., A5 to B2),
%e A319476 2) 2*sqrt(2)  (e.g., A5 to C7),
%e A319476 3) 4*sqrt(2)  (e.g., B2 to F6),
%e A319476 4) 2*sqrt(10) (e.g., A5 to G3), and
%e A319476 5)   sqrt(26) (e.g., A5 to F6).
